</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-34_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong> Ofcom </strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-36_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Ofcom is the UK’s communications regulator, established by the Office of Communications Act 2002. It ensures the optimal use of the radio spectrum, promotes competition, and protects consumers from harmful or offensive material.
























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-38_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Communications Act 2003
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-40_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The primary legislation governing Ofcom’s duties, this Act covers various aspects of the communication sector, from television and radio broadcasting to internet services.


























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-42_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Regulatory compliance
